<subSubSection id="4FFC65060B7B164A78E8FEB4262CFE71" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="0759368D0B7B164A78E8FEB4262CFE71" blockId="11.[136,1452,266,761]" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B7B164A78E8FEB426C8FE39" bold="true" box="[189,402,374,400]" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B7B164A79FBFEB42519FE39" box="[430,579,374,400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linifolia">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B7B164A79FBFEB42519FE39" box="[430,579,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Sida linifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a species of section 
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B7B164A7B00FEB42499FE39" box="[853,963,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Stenindae</emphasis>
(
<tableCitation id="4A6403360B7B164A7B80FEB42371FE39" box="[981,1067,374,400]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,224,340,364]" captionTargetBox="[144,1440,425,1289]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Sections of Sida with species occurring in Rio Grande do Sul state, and their diagnostic features, according to Fryxell (1985) and Krapovickas (2003)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" tableUuid="539966050B72164378DDFE962568FE39">Table 1</tableCitation>
), easily distinguished from other species of the genus by its entire, narrowly linear or broadly lanceolate leaf blades and by the indehiscent mericarps (
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B7B164A78C5FE7C2670FE71" box="[144,298,446,472]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1920,1942]" captionTargetBox="[248,1340,353,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-118@10.[248,1340,353,1895]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 4. A–F. Sida farroupilhensis. A. Flower. B. Abaxial surface of leaf. C. Adaxial surface of leaf. D. Mature schizocarp. E. Mature and immature schizocarps. F. Branch with leaves and flowers buds. G–J Sida linifolia. G. Abaxial surface of leaf. H. Buds in terminal umbelliform inflorescence. I. Schizocarps and buds in terminal umbelliform inflorescence J. Branch with flowers and buds. K–Q. Sida lonchitis. K. Flowers. L, N. Adaxial surface of leaf. M. Abaxial surface of leaf. O. Terminal inflorescence. P. Bifid bracts (black arrow). Q. Schizocarps. Photographs I–J by Luís Funez, all others by Martin Grings (G–J from N.I. Matzenbacher, ICN 123026)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415495/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Figures 4G–J</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B7B164A7960FE7C2630FE71" box="[309,362,446,472]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="26.[136,229,1957,1979]" captionTargetBox="[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetId="figure-54@26.[196,1391,245,1933]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 14. Mericarps. A. Sida anomala. B. Sida confusa. C. Sida farroupilhensis. D. Sida glaziovii. E. Sida cerradoensis. F. Sida cordifolia. G. Sida dubia. H. Sida linifolia. I. Sida lonchitis. J. Sida nemorensis. K. Sida paradoxa. L. Sida planicaulis. M. Sida potentilloides.N. Sida reitzii. O. Sida regnellii. P. Sida rhombifolia.Q. Sida riedelii. R. Sida rubifolia.S. Sida spinosa.T. Sida tuberculata. U. Sida urens. V. Sida viarum. Photographs by Martin Grings." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415519" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415519/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">14H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4FFC65060B7B164A78E8FE20267DFD25" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="0759368D0B7B164A78E8FE20267DFD25" blockId="11.[136,1452,266,761]" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B7B164A78E8FE2025BEFE55" bold="true" box="[189,740,482,508]" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Distribution, habitat and conservation status:</emphasis>
—The species is widely distributed, from 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B7B164A7C90FE202241FE55" box="[1221,1307,482,508]" name="Mexico" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Mexico</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B7B164A7D14FE2022D2FE55" box="[1345,1416,482,508]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, in parts of Africa, and 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B7B164A7933FDC426D7FD89" box="[358,397,518,544]" name="Fiji" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Fiji</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B7B164A79CEFDC4256AFD88" author="Fryxell, P. A." box="[411,560,518,545]" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" pagination="62 - 91" refId="ref18743" refString="Fryxell, P. A. (1985) The North and Central American species of Sida. Sida, Contributions to Botany 11: 62 - 91." type="journal article" year="1985">Fryxell 1985</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry id="7FF1761D0B7B164A7A34FDC425FFFD89" box="[609,677,518,544]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Brazil</collectingCountry>
<taxonomicName id="C0E64D0E0B7B164A7AF9FDC42464FD89" box="[684,830,518,544]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="linifolia">
<emphasis id="3592EA9F0B7B164A7AF9FDC42464FD89" box="[684,830,518,544]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Sida linifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in all states (
<bibRefCitation id="63774B7C0B7B164A7C4AFDC423F4FD89" author="Bovini, M. G." box="[1055,1198,518,544]" pageId="11" pageNumber="116" refId="ref18092" refString="Bovini, M. G. (2020) Sida in Lista de Especies da Flora do Brasil. Jardim Botanico do Rio de Janeiro. Available from: http: // floradobrasil. jbrj. gov. br / jabot / floradobrasil / FB 9206 (accessed 7 July 2020)" type="url" year="2020">Bovini 2020</bibRefCitation>
) and in 
<collectingRegion id="C522F86F0B7B164A7D52FDC427F7FDED" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
only in two localities in Inland sub-montane grassland (
<figureCitation id="9FDD2A080B7B164A7B78FDE824CAFDEC" box="[813,912,554,581]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="12.[136,229,2030,2052]" captionTargetBox="[315,1294,482,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-118@12.[258,1329,425,2006]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distribution map of Sida glaziovii, S. paradoxa, S. linifolia, S. nemorensis, S. planicaulis, S. potentilloides and S. rubifolia in Rio Grande do Sul state, Brazil." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415497" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415497/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="116">Figure 5</figureCitation>
). The species is here considered Least Concern (LC) because it has large EOO and AOO, since it is a frequent and often ruderal species and is present in more than one continent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
